  "response": "Let me help you with this.\n\nTo find the chemical formula for ammonium oxide:\n1. Ammonium ion (NH4+) has a charge of +1\n2. Oxide ion (O2-) has a charge of -2\n3. To balance the charges, you need 2 ammonium ions for every 1 oxide ion\n4. The resulting chemical formula is (NH4)2O\n\nSome uses of ammonium oxide include:\n1. Used in fertilizer production\n2. Potential applications in chemical manufacturing\n3. Can be used as a reagent in some laboratory experiments\n4. May have some use in cleaning and industrial processes\n\nHowever, it's worth noting that ammonium oxide is not a very stable compound and is less commonly used compared to other ammonium compounds. Most references discuss its theoretical structure rather than practical applications.\n\nIn practice, ammonia (NH3) and water (H2O) are more commonly used in industrial and chemical processes.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any part of this explanation?",
